null,&quot;height&quot;:821,&quot;width&quot;:1294,&quot;resizeWidth&quot;:null,&quot;bytes&quot;:319120,&quot;alt&quot;:null,&quot;title&quot;:null,&quot;type&quot;:&quot;image/jpeg&quot;,&quot;href&quot;:null,&quot;belowTheFold&quot;:false,&quot;topImage&quot;:true,&quot;internalRedirect&quot;:null,&quot;isProcessing&quot;:false}" class="sizing-normal" alt="" srcset="https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_424,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F0a0b336e-5fa9-4cad-8ba2-980e33a692a3_1294x821.jpeg 424w, https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_848,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F0a0b336e-5fa9-4cad-8ba2-980e33a692a3_1294x821.jpeg 848w, https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_1272,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F0a0b336e-5fa9-4cad-8ba2-980e33a692a3_1294x821.jpeg 1272w, https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_1456,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F0a0b336e-5fa9-4cad-8ba2-980e33a692a3_1294x821.jpeg 1456w" sizes="100vw" fetchpriority="high"></picture><div class="image-link-expand"><svg xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg" width="20" height="20" viewBox="0 0 24 24" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2" stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" class="lucide lucide-maximize2 "><polyline points="15 3 21 3 21 9"></polyline><polyline points="9 21 3 21 3 15"></polyline><line x1="21" x2="14" y1="3" y2="10"></line><line x1="3" x2="10" y1="21" y2="14"></line></svg></div></div></a><figcaption class="image-caption"><em>Image Credit-Midjourney</em></figcaption></figure></div><p class="button-wrapper" data-attrs="{&quot;url&quot;:&quot;https://timdenning.substack.com/p/the-best-feeling-in-the-world-is-024?utm_source=substack&amp;utm_medium=email&amp;utm_content=share&amp;action=share&quot;,&quot;text&quot;:&quot;Share&quot;,&quot;action&quot;:null,&quot;class&quot;:null}" data-component-name="ButtonCreateButton"><a class="button primary" href="https://timdenning.substack.com/p/the-best-feeling-in-the-world-is-024?utm_source=substack&amp;utm_medium=email&amp;utm_content=share&amp;action=share"><span>Share</span></a></p><p>Work feels like death for most people.</p><p>99% of people don‚Äôt describe their work as play. This idea sounds like clickbait Alex Hormozi garbage to the masses.</p><p>It feels like it‚Äôs time to roll out the cliche ‚ÄúDo what you love little Timmy Tucker.‚Äù Over the last few years I‚Äôve turned my life into a video game. The only objective of this game is I want to keep playing it forever.</p><p>That means I need to continue to get paid to play this game. The difference here is I‚Äôm not doing the work I do to earn money or get rich. I just want to keep doing this type of work that feels like play to me.</p><p>It‚Äôs a radical mindset that blows up most people‚Äôs brains.</p><p>I didn‚Äôt invent this way of life, and I stumbled across it by pure accident. Here‚Äôs how you, too, can get paid to play and experience what is the best feeling in the world.</p><h1>Don‚Äôt play stupid games with stupid people</h1><p>The most important goals always start with figuring out what you don‚Äôt want (also known as anti-goals).</p><p>I used to spend my days in meeting rooms playing stupid games with stupid people. I never got anything done. Even changing a logo on a sales page required a committee of pinheads to agree.</p><p>I‚Äôd wake up and answer stupid work emails that a chatbot could easily answer. I‚Äôd sell stupid bank products that I didn‚Äôt agree with to stupid people who thought these products would make them rich (banking products make the bank rich, not you).</p><p>I disliked most people I met in business. They were so mediocre.</p><p>They‚Äôd have Friday drinks, get drunk, watch the football, and talk about some meaningless Netflix show. It all felt so ‚Ä¶ boring. I accepted this boredom as my reality. I‚Äôd never known any other way to live.</p><p>My life felt stupid.</p><p>I eventually got off this hamster wheel. I discovered that people were building new careers for themselves on the internet with no boss and no employer. It seemed like clickbait at the start until I was surrounded by an army of people living this way.</p><p>They chose a topic, made it their obsession, then centered their whole life around it. I discovered they turned their life into a video game.</p><h1>Get paid to keep playing the video game you obsess over</h1><p>Once I succeeded at online writing it was all I wanted to do.</p><p>When I quit my 9-5 job the stakes became higher. My mantra became, ‚ÄúHow do I keep getting paid to play this amazing video game?‚Äù It wasn‚Äôt a game of survival or trying to become a rich b*tch so I could buy a Lambo and take selfies in Santa Monica.</p><p>I just wanted to keep living the video game‚Ä¶</p><ul><li><p>Wake up whenever</p></li><li><p>See my daughter whenever</p></li><li><p>Goof off a day a week</p></li><li><p>Walk in the sunshine</p></li><li><p>Hit the gym 4 times a week (whenever)</p></li><li><p>Work from home or an Airbnb anywhere in the world</p></li><li><p>Never get told what to do by a micro-managing boss ever again</p></li><li><p>Write every day without filtering who I am or worrying about opinions</p></li></ul><p>So I set up my online business to do that.</p><p>This meant I had to‚Ä¶</p><ol><li><p>Find predictable income streams</p></li><li><p>Make money from my strengths</p></li><li><p>Find ways to make recurring revenue</p></li><li><p>Learn how to craft high-ticket offers ($10,000+)</p></li><li><p>Build affiliate partnerships</p></li><li><p>Grow my email list</p></li><li><p>Figure out how to get predictable traffic to my email list</p></li></ol><p>These seven steps allowed me to set up a foundation to keep getting paid for the rest of my life. It‚Äôs the kind of feeling I can‚Äôt describe. I‚Äôm 100% self-sufficient and will never ask an employer for a salary again. It‚Äôs what I call the permissionless life.</p><p>Here are the steps if you want to do the same.</p><h1>1. Turn an ‚Äúinterest‚Äù into an obsession</h1><p>There‚Äôs a threshold of participation most people never reach.</p><p>It‚Äôs easy to get h0rny when you‚Äôre in the virgin territory of a new interest. Those first few weeks of a new interest are orgasmic. But after the endorphins wear off the average person can‚Äôt keep the habit of an interest long enough to get results.</p><p>They need dopamine. They need the ear candy of compliments and strangers kissing their smelly feet to keep going.</p><p>The only way to overcome this ‚Äúinterest‚Äù problem is to dial up the intensity. </p><p>I call it ‚Äúgoing all in.‚Äù You must fully commit. </p><ul><li><p>For some people that means quitting their job. </p></li><li><p>For others it means giving up all their other hobbies. </p></li><li><p>In my case it meant dumping my ex-girlfriend so I could get rid of all BS distractions and focus on online writing.</p></li></ul><p>It also means putting ya money where ya big mouth is.</p><p><em>Interest</em> is hard to maintain. When you invest money in an interest you start to expect an ROI. That gives you leverage on your lazy self (a side we all have) to wake up early and actually put in the work.</p><p>No money, no commitment.</p><p>Interests need to peculate for long enough too. The 10,000-hour rule is a good rule of thumb. But doing the same thing over and over and expecting results is the definition of insanity. The 10,000-hour rule also needs 10,000 iterations.</p><p>To dial up the intensity to the max you also need to be around other people on their way to obsession who care about similar things. Obsession is an identity. It‚Äôs not for everyone, but without it you stay a no one.</p><p>Go all in or don‚Äôt get paid to play. Ever.</p><blockquote><p><em>Obsession turns average people into outliers ‚Äì Zach Pogrob</em></p></blockquote><h1>2. Value growth more than you value safety</h1><p>I spoke to a guy today.</p><p>His email started with ‚ÄúI‚Äôm obsessed.‚Äù He then went on to tell me he‚Äôs only willing to explore his obsession if it‚Äôs free. He won‚Äôt invest in anything from anyone. I suggested a $100 option he could try from a creator I admire. He still wouldn‚Äôt do it.</p><pre><code>If you won‚Äôt invest $100 in your obsession, you‚Äôre not obsessed.</code></pre><p>You‚Äôre lying to yourself. Where we invest money helps us to understand what we care about. Mastery in any field isn‚Äôt free.</p><p>(For some reason people will pay $100K for a mostly useless college degree though.) What stops us investing in our obsession is we‚Äôre taught to value safety more than we are to take risks.</p><pre><code>An investment always carries some risk but so, too, does playing it safe.</code></pre><p>People spend so much time trying to protect the little they already got, that they miss out on the enormous upside they could have by investing in their obsession.</p><p><strong>Most people‚Äôs security blankets aren‚Äôt worth protecting.</strong> $20,000 in savings feels like a lot, but you can never really live an extraordinary life with it.</p><p>You‚Äôll always be one step away from broke. One curveball. One medical disaster. One parking fine. Bam. It‚Äôs all gone. Mayday, mayday. That‚Äôs no way to live.</p><p>Protecting the little you have is a sign of a scarcity mindset. Obsession is fuelled by a growth mindset grounded in optimism.</p><p>You must believe life can be better than it is to truly get paid to play for the rest of your life.</p><h1>3. Get so good people pay you</h1><p>Work that feels like play doesn‚Äôt turn into money until you get good.</p><p>In my case, there are a lot of writers online. Anyone can write. But most never get paid to do it every day because they don‚Äôt master the video game. Like anything, there are a stack of micro skills needed to go beyond the average results most will achieve.</p><p>On the surface it looks like all you need to do is write. Once you get far enough into the game you realize there‚Äôs 100x more to it.</p><p>At this point you can either get overwhelmed and frustrated by it, or you can play the game and push yourself to mastery. Either way, people won‚Äôt pay until you get good.</p><p>So you either good, or keep falling short and wondering why you never can get paid to do work that feels like play while others do it and make it look easy.</p><p>I don‚Äôt make the rules. Use obsession to get good or give up.</p><p>There are millions of office cubicle jobs on LinkedIn right now that‚Äôd be glad to have you, so you can play boring office games until 65, then die. Choose wisely.</p><h1>4. ‚ÄúWork turns into play when improvement turns into <s>passion</s> obsession‚Äù</h1><p>(Dan Koe)</p><p>There‚Äôs a meme on Twitter/X that goes ‚ÄúXYZ thing is self-improvement in disguise.</p><ul><li><p>Business is self-improvement in disguise.</p></li><li><p>Gym is self-improvement in disguise.</p></li><li><p>Leadership is self-improvement in disguise.</p></li><li><p>Losing weight is self-improvement in disguise.</p></li><li><p>Writing is self-improvement in disguise.</p></li></ul><p>All of these and more are true. What makes a goal a video game that‚Äôs fun to play is when improvement is built in.</p><p>As Dan Koe says, work turns into play when you force yourself to improve. This improvement mechanism is how you progress from an interest to an obsession. That‚Äôs what happened with me and writing.</p><p>I kept wanting to improve. I kept challenging myself to write better essays, do more research, and attract more email subscribers. The improvement aspect is now automated. It‚Äôs a flywheel that keeps on spinning and won‚Äôt die out until I die.</p><p>Not improving is where people go wrong.</p><p>We‚Äôve all seen it. You know, the friend who sells their arts and crafts at the Sunday market each week and is still doing the same number of sales that they did a year ago. Or worse, their sales keep plummeting.</p><p>They never move out of hobby mode because they haven‚Äôt set up systems to force improvement. And they refuse to pay for help or consider the real fact their business is sh*t and will never make money.</p><p>1%-better-each-day is cheesy as hell because it works.</p><h1>Closing Thought</h1><p>The best goal you can ever have is to turn a passion into an obsession, then get paid to play this infinite video game for the rest of your life.</p><p>Somehow I figured out this glitch in the matrix. I‚Äôm not the only one. Every day more people are building small online empires around their obsession. If you‚Äôre bored in life, it‚Äôs time to migrate to a new way of living.</p><p>Tell me which of these ideas above you find useful and why in the comments.</p><div><hr></div><p>I send this email weekly. If you would also like to receive it, join the 127,000+ other smart people who absolutely love it today.</p><p class="button-wrapper" data-attrs="{&quot;url&quot;:&quot;https://timdenning.substack.com/subscribe?&quot;,&quot;text&quot;:&quot;Subscribe now&quot;,&quot;action&quot;:null,&quot;class&quot;:null}" data-component-name="ButtonCreateButton"><a class="button primary" href="https://timdenning.substack.com/subscribe?"><span>Subscribe now</span></a></p><p>üëâ&nbsp;If you enjoy reading this post, feel free to share it with friends! Or feel free to click the ‚ù§Ô∏è button on this post so more people can discover it on Substack üôè</p><p class="button-wrapper" data-attrs="{&quot;url&quot;:&quot;https://timdenning.substack.com/p/the-best-feeling-in-the-world-is-024?utm_source=substack&amp;utm_medium=email&amp;utm_content=share&amp;action=share&quot;,&quot;text&quot;:&quot;Share&quot;,&quot;action&quot;:null,&quot;class&quot;:null}" data-component-name="ButtonCreateButton"><a class="button primary" href="https://timdenning.substack.com/p/the-best-feeling-in-the-world-is-024?utm_source=substack&amp;utm_medium=email&amp;utm_content=share&amp;action=share"><span>Share</span></a></p></body></html>	Turn work into play by obsessing over improvement. Get so good people pay you. Value growth over safety. Build a life around your passion.	2024-10-01 11:53:11	2024-10-05 19:39:33.149	2024-10-10 14:04:45.026	{english}	https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F0a0b336e-5fa9-4cad-8ba2-980e33a692a3_1294x821.jpeg	Tim Denning	the-best-feeling-in-the-world-is-getting-paid-to-play
100	https://rogerpielkejr.substack.com/p/the-clean-energy-transitions-voter	The Clean Energy Transition‚Äôs Voter Problem	They‚Äôre just not that interested	<html><head></head><body><div class="captioned-image-container"><figure><a class="image-link image2 is-viewable-imag" target="_blank" href="https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F6ead4376-2166-48da-9597-25624dbefb19_1018x582.png" data-component-name="Image2ToDOM"><div class="image2-inset"><picture><source type="image/webp" srcset="https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_424,c_limit,f_webp,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F6ead4376-2166-48da-9597-25624dbefb19_1018x582.png 424w, https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_848,c_limit,f_webp,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F6ead4376-2166-48da-9597-25624dbefb19_1018x582.png 848w, https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_1272,c_limit,f_webp,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F6ead4376-2166-48da-9597-25624dbefb19_1018x582.png 1272w, https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_1456,c_limit,f_webp,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F6ead4376-2166-48da-9597-25624dbefb19_1018x582.png 1456w" sizes="100vw"><img src="https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_1456,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F6ead4376-2166-48da-9597-25624dbefb19_1018x582.png" width="711" height="406.4852652259332" data-attrs="{&quot;src&quot;:&quot;https://substack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com/public/images/6ead4376-2166-48da-9597-25624dbefb19_1018x582.png&quot;,&quot;srcNoWatermark&quot;:null,&quot;fullscreen&quot;:null,&quot;imageSize&quot;:null,&quot;height&quot;:582,&quot;width&quot;:1018,&quot;resizeWidth&quot;:711,&quot;bytes&quot;:1716159,&quot;alt&quot;:null,&quot;title&quot;:null,&quot;type&quot;:&quot;image/png&quot;,&quot;href&quot;:null,&quot;belowTheFold&quot;:false,&quot;topImage&quot;:true,&quot;internalRedirect&quot;:null,&quot;isProcessing&quot;:false}" class="sizing-normal" alt="" srcset="https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_424,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F6ead4376-2166-48da-9597-25624dbefb19_1018x582.png 424w, https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_848,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F6ead4376-2166-48da-9597-25624dbefb19_1018x582.png 848w, https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_1272,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F6ead4376-2166-48da-9597-25624dbefb19_1018x582.png 1272w, https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_1456,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F6ead4376-2166-48da-9597-25624dbefb19_1018x582.png 1456w" sizes="100vw" fetchpriority="high"></picture><div class="image-link-expand"><svg xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg" width="20" height="20" viewBox="0 0 24 24" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2" stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" class="lucide lucide-maximize2 "><polyline points="15 3 21 3 21 9"></polyline><polyline points="9 21 3 21 3 15"></polyline><line x1="21" x2="14" y1="3" y2="10"></line><line x1="3" x2="10" y1="21" y2="14"></line></svg></div></div></a><figcaption class="image-caption">Get out and vote!</figcaption></figure></div><p><em>Note: This post is co-authored with <a href="https://substack.com/@theliberalpatriot">Ruy Teixeira</a>, a colleague of mine at the American Enterprise Institute, and is being co-published with <a href="https://www.liberalpatriot.com/p/the-clean-energy-transitions-voter">The Liberal Patriot</a> ‚Äî to which you should of course subscribe. Today we report the first topline results of a project we are collaborating on focused on better understanding the views of ordinary Americans on energy and climate. We present the eye-opening highlights of a new detailed YouGov survey of Americans on climate and energy ‚Äî a survey that we designed and conducted a few weeks ago. ‚ÄîRP</em></p><p class="button-wrapper" data-attrs="{&quot;url&quot;:&quot;https://rogerpielkejr.substack.com/subscribe?&quot;,&quot;text&quot;:&quot;Subscribe now&quot;,&quot;action&quot;:null,&quot;class&quot;:null}" data-component-name="ButtonCreateButton"><a class="button primary" href="https://rogerpielkejr.substack.com/subscribe?"><span>Subscribe now</span></a></p><p>The future of the clean energy transition is cloudy. It‚Äôs well-known that there are disagreements‚Äîwide disagreements‚Äîbetween Republicans and Democrats about our energy future. But less well-known is the bedrock of public opinion on America‚Äôs energy supply, the importance of a rapid transition away from fossil fuels, and the general salience of the climate change issue.</p><p>Findings from a new YouGov survey indicate that most voters‚Äô views differ quite a bit from those of rapid energy transition advocates. These views constitute an ineluctable reality that any transition, on any timetable, will have to deal with. At the same time there is political opportunity here to better align policy priorities with voter preferences.</p><p>This survey is part of a broader study conducted by Roger Pielke, Jr. and Ruy Teixeira of the American Enterprise Institute that seeks to compare scientific understandings of energy and climate with dominant public narratives on these issues and how both compare to the views of actual voters.</p><p>The full study and polling data will be released after the election but here we present ten of the most interesting findings from our new survey that shed light on the current debate around climate and energy issues.</p><p>1. <em><strong>An "all of the above" approach to energy policy has by far the most voter support and shows remarkable stability and common support across voter groups</strong>.</em></p><p>When presented with a choice among three options‚Äîa rapid green energy transition, an ‚Äúall of the above‚Äù energy policy, and emphasizing fossil fuels‚ÄîAmerican voters across demographics and partisanship strongly prefer an ‚Äúall of the above‚Äù approach to energy policy including oil, gas, renewables, and nuclear. Less than a quarter support a rapid transition to renewables, which drops to under a fifth for working-class (noncollege) voters. Even among Democrats, support for a rapid transition is only a little over a third.</p><p>2. <em><strong>On extreme weather events, most voters have not accepted the apocalyptic reporting found in the media and pushed by climate activists</strong>.</em></p><p>Most people hold views of trends in extreme weather events that are consistent with the most recent assessment of the Intergovernmental Panel on Climate Change (IPCC). They do <em>not</em> say they have personally observed an increase in hurricanes, floods, drought, or tornadoes which is consistent with the current state of scientific understandings. The exception is heat waves where, consistent with the IPCC, a majority report that they have observed an increase in such events.</p><p>3. <em><strong>American voters are reluctant to pay even a small amount to support climate action and this willingness drops quickly as the proposed small costs increase</strong></em>.</p><p>When asked if they would support just a $1 monthly fee on their electricity bill to fight climate change, only 47 percent say they would while almost as many (43 percent) are opposed. Even at this level, opposition is greater than support among working-class voters. When the proposed fee is increased to $20, overall voter support plummets to 26 percent with 60 percent opposed. At $40, it is 19 percent support to 69 percent opposition; at $75 it is 15 percent vs. 72 percent; and at $100 it is 7:1 against (77 percent to 11 percent) paying such a fee to combat climate change.</p><p>4. <em><strong>Voters expect an energy transition away from fossil fuels to lead to unexpected problems</strong>.</em></p><p>About two-thirds think problems are likely. A follow-up question indicates that voters are most worried about the impact on the prices of energy and everyday goods and about the impact on the reliability of the electrical grid. Voters are most positive about the impact of an energy transition on job opportunities in the energy sector and on air and water quality.</p><p>5. <em><strong>Overall, the public is much more favorable on both solar and natural gas than on wind, suggesting that the concept of "renewables" masks some important differences</strong>.</em></p><p>Solar energy tests the best among five energy sources that voters were asked to rank. Thirty-eight percent of voters ranked solar first. Natural gas did the second best, picked first by 26 percent of voters. Nuclear energy came third (15 percent ranked it first) followed by wind (10 percent) and coal (6 percent). Coal is clearly the least preferred energy source with 38 percent ranking it dead last among options. Wind and nuclear also have strong opposition with, respectively, 19 percent and 29 percent ranking the technology their least favorite option.</p><p class="button-wrapper" data-attrs="{&quot;url&quot;:&quot;https://www.liberalpatriot.com/p/the-clean-energy-transitions-voter?utm_source=substack&amp;utm_medium=email&amp;utm_content=share&amp;action=share&amp;token=eyJ1c2VyX2lkIjo0NDM0MTg3LCJwb3N0X2lkIjoxNDk5ODA5MDcsImlhdCI6MTcyODU2NTU0NSwiZXhwIjoxNzMxMTU3NTQ1LCJpc3MiOiJwdWItMjM5MDU4Iiwic3ViIjoicG9zdC1yZWFjdGlvbiJ9.0EkXBMnesXBGELGduAQzpEuYTW4rH7FPqE7uTIB4Gns&quot;,&quot;text&quot;:&quot;Share&quot;,&quot;action&quot;:null,&quot;class&quot;:&quot;button-wrapper&quot;}" data-component-name="ButtonCreateButton"><a class="button primary button-wrapper" href="https://www.liberalpatriot.com/p/the-clean-energy-transitions-voter?utm_source=substack&amp;utm_medium=email&amp;utm_content=share&amp;action=share&amp;token=eyJ1c2VyX2lkIjo0NDM0MTg3LCJwb3N0X2lkIjoxNDk5ODA5MDcsImlhdCI6MTcyODU2NTU0NSwiZXhwIjoxNzMxMTU3NTQ1LCJpc3MiOiJwdWItMjM5MDU4Iiwic3ViIjoicG9zdC1yZWFjdGlvbiJ9.0EkXBMnesXBGELGduAQzpEuYTW4rH7FPqE7uTIB4Gns"><span>Share</span></a></p><p>6. <em><strong>In terms of the energy they consume, cost and reliability are way, way more important to voters than possible effects on the climate</strong>.</em></p><p>Given four choices, 37 percent of voters said the cost of the energy they use was most important to them and 36 percent said the availability of power when they need it was most important. Just 19 percent thought the effect on climate of their energy consumption was most important and 6 percent selected the effect on U.S. energy security.</p><p>7. <em><strong>In terms of proposals to mitigate the effects of climate change, getting to ‚Äúnet zero‚Äù as quickly as possible is relatively unimportant to voters</strong>.</em></p><p>Asked to consider proposals to reduce the effects of global climate change, voters were least likely to say ‚Äúgetting the U.S. to net zero carbon emissions as quickly as possible‚Äù was very important to them personally (29 percent), fewer than said ‚Äúlimiting the burden of regulations on business‚Äù was very important (32 percent). Voters were most likely by far to say keeping consumer costs low (66 percent) and increasing jobs and economic growth (60 percent) were very important aspects of climate mitigation proposals. The split was wider among working-class voters: 71 percent thought keeping consumer costs low was very important, compared to 26 percent who thought rapidly getting to net zero was very important.</p><p>8. <em><strong>Climate change as an issue has very low salience to voters</strong>.</em></p><p>Voters were asked to evaluate a list of 18 issue areas and rate their priority for the president and Congress to address in the coming year. As a ‚Äútop priority,‚Äù dealing with global climate change ranked 15<sup>th</sup> out of these 18 areas, well behind strengthening the national economy, fighting inflation, defending the country from terrorist attacks, and keeping Social Security financially sound‚Äîand also behind reducing health care costs, dealing with immigration, improving the educational system, keeping energy costs low, reducing the budget deficit, reducing crime, improving how the political system works, improving the job situation, strengthening the military, and dealing with the problems of poor people. The climate issue only ranked above global trade, drug addiction, and issues around race.</p><p>9. <em><strong>Voters support increased domestic production of fossil fuels, but they are unaware fossil fuel production has actually increased in the last several years</strong>.</em></p><p>By 22 points (56-34), voters favor more domestic production of fossil fuels‚Äîoil and gas. Working-class voters felt even more strongly, endorsing the idea by 30 points. But only 17 percent of voters are aware that the Biden administration has increased oil production on federal lands. However, when informed that the U.S. has, in fact, increased domestic production of oil and gas in the last several years, they are delighted. Almost seven in ten (69 percent) said ‚Äúthis is a positive development, which brings good jobs for U.S. workers, ensures our energy supply and helps the U.S. support our allies who need similar resources‚Äù compared to 31 percent who thought ‚Äúthis is a negative development, which brings more pollution, climate change, and continued reliance on fossil fuels.‚Äù</p><p>10. <em><strong>Voter interest in electric heat pumps, hot water heaters and stoves, as well as electric vehicles, is weak</strong>.</em></p><p>Asked whether they had given serious thought to making certain ‚Äúgreen‚Äù changes in their home within the past 12 months, 75 percent of voters said they either had not given serious thought to installing an electric heat pump or that that device was not relevant to them; 67 percent said the same thing about an electric water heater as did 61 percent about an electric stove or induction system.</p><p>Voters by 17 points (52-35) say they are opposed to phasing out new gasoline cars and trucks by 2035 and many more voters are upset (48 percent) than excited (21 percent) by the idea of phasing out production of gas-powered cars and trucks. By 18 points (59-41), voters say they are not likely to even consider purchasing an electric vehicle as their next car. Just 10 percent say they now own an electric vehicle and two-thirds of those are hybrid rather than fully electric. </p><p class="button-wrapper" data-attrs="{&quot;url&quot;:&quot;https://rogerpielkejr.substack.com/p/the-clean-energy-transitions-voter/comments&quot;,&quot;text&quot;:&quot;Leave a comment&quot;,&quot;action&quot;:null,&quot;class&quot;:null}" data-component-name="ButtonCreateButton"><a class="button primary" href="https://rogerpielkejr.substack.com/p/the-clean-energy-transitions-voter/comments"><span>Leave a comment</span></a></p><p><em>Thanks for reading and commenting! In coming weeks and months, Ruy and I will be sharing more from our survey and what it signifies for U.S. energy and climate policies. We welcome your questions and reactions here or at <a href="https://www.liberalpatriot.com/p/the-clean-energy-transitions-voter">The Liberal Patriot</a>. Remember, THB is reader supported ‚Äî So please support! </em></p><p class="button-wrapper" data-attrs="{&quot;url&quot;:&quot;https://rogerpielkejr.substack.com/subscribe?&quot;,&quot;text&quot;:&quot;Subscribe now&quot;,&quot;action&quot;:null,&quot;class&quot;:null}" data-component-name="ButtonCreateButton"><a class="button primary" href="https://rogerpielkejr.substack.com/subscribe?"><span>Subscribe now</span></a></p></body></html>	Voters prefer an "all of the above" energy policy, are reluctant to pay for climate action, and have low interest in electric vehicles and home appliances. Findings suggest a mismatch between public opinion and rapid energy transition advocacy.	2024-10-10 13:22:31	2024-10-10 13:35:06.848	2024-10-10 14:04:46.627	{english}	https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F6ead4376-2166-48da-9597-25624dbefb19_1018x582.png	Roger Pielke Jr.	the-clean-energy-transitions-voter-problem
103	https://timdenning.substack.com/p/being-a-high-performer-is-lonely	Being a High Performer Is Lonely as Hell	It's also the best feeling in the world	<html><head></head><body><div class="captioned-image-container"><figure><a class="image-link image2 is-viewable-imag" target="_blank" href="https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2Fb03c8cad-ea12-4bd1-bf08-08dad0ebb560_1042x667.jpeg" data-component-name="Image2ToDOM"><div class="image2-inset"><picture><source type="image/webp" srcset="https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_424,c_limit,f_webp,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2Fb03c8cad-ea12-4bd1-bf08-08dad0ebb560_1042x667.jpeg 424w, https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_848,c_limit,f_webp,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2Fb03c8cad-ea12-4bd1-bf08-08dad0ebb560_1042x667.jpeg 848w, https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_1272,c_limit,f_webp,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2Fb03c8cad-ea12-4bd1-bf08-08dad0ebb560_1042x667.jpeg 1272w, https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_1456,c_limit,f_webp,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2Fb03c8cad-ea12-4bd1-bf08-08dad0ebb560_1042x667.jpeg 1456w" sizes="100vw"><img src="https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_1456,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2Fb03c8cad-ea12-4bd1-bf08-08dad0ebb560_1042x667.jpeg" width="1042" height="667" data-attrs="{&quot;src&quot;:&quot;https://substack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com/public/images/b03c8cad-ea12-4bd1-bf08-08dad0ebb560_1042x667.jpeg&quot;,&quot;srcNoWatermark&quot;:null,&quot;fullscreen&quot;:null,&quot;imageSize&quot;:null,&quot;height&quot;:667,&quot;width&quot;:1042,&quot;resizeWidth&quot;:null,&quot;bytes&quot;:194937,&quot;alt&quot;:null,&quot;title&quot;:null,&quot;type&quot;:&quot;image/jpeg&quot;,&quot;href&quot;:null,&quot;belowTheFold&quot;:false,&quot;topImage&quot;:true,&quot;internalRedirect&quot;:null,&quot;isProcessing&quot;:false}" class="sizing-normal" alt="" srcset="https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_424,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2Fb03c8cad-ea12-4bd1-bf08-08dad0ebb560_1042x667.jpeg 424w, https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_848,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2Fb03c8cad-ea12-4bd1-bf08-08dad0ebb560_1042x667.jpeg 848w, https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_1272,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2Fb03c8cad-ea12-4bd1-bf08-08dad0ebb560_1042x667.jpeg 1272w, https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_1456,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2Fb03c8cad-ea12-4bd1-bf08-08dad0ebb560_1042x667.jpeg 1456w" sizes="100vw" fetchpriority="high"></picture><div class="image-link-expand"><svg xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg" width="20" height="20" viewBox="0 0 24 24" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2" stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" class="lucide lucide-maximize2 "><polyline points="15 3 21 3 21 9"></polyline><polyline points="9 21 3 21 3 15"></polyline><line x1="21" x2="14" y1="3" y2="10"></line><line x1="3" x2="10" y1="21" y2="14"></line></svg></div></div></a><figcaption class="image-caption"><em>Image Credit-Midjourney</em></figcaption></figure></div><p class="button-wrapper" data-attrs="{&quot;url&quot;:&quot;https://timdenning.substack.com/p/being-a-high-performer-is-lonely?utm_source=substack&amp;utm_medium=email&amp;utm_content=share&amp;action=share&quot;,&quot;text&quot;:&quot;Share&quot;,&quot;action&quot;:null,&quot;class&quot;:null}" data-component-name="ButtonCreateButton"><a class="button primary" href="https://timdenning.substack.com/p/being-a-high-performer-is-lonely?utm_source=substack&amp;utm_medium=email&amp;utm_content=share&amp;action=share"><span>Share</span></a></p><p>High performance often feels like elitism.</p><p>You‚Äôre either successful or a loser. No in between. That view of the world is a little harsh for my liking. As always the truth lies in the nuance.</p><p>I never used to see myself as a high performer. My younger years were full of failures. My childhood was too. We lost our family home not once but twice. Kids used to make fun of me.</p><p>In 2013 my entire world changed forever.</p><p>I went to a Tony Robbins seminar that rewired my brain. I started to think differently. That made me weird which made me feel good. For the last 11 years, I‚Äôve been on the path of high performance and in the top 1% of my field.</p><p>High performers aren‚Äôt what they seem. You‚Äôve been lied to.</p><h1>Lie #1 ‚Äì There‚Äôs a lot of competition</h1><p>No there isn‚Äôt.</p><p>What I do is lonely because there isn‚Äôt any real competition. And when there is a competitor, they last about 6 months and then give up or go out of business.</p><p>When there‚Äôs no competition it feels lonely. You have no one to aspire to be like. It‚Äôs hard to find idols. What you do can even feel boring.</p><p>So the problem to solve isn‚Äôt that you‚Äôll have so many competitors no one will pay attention to what you do. No. The problem is that you‚Äôll discover there is no competition and feel lonely.</p><p>Learning to deal with the loneliness is not always easy, but it‚Äôs an attribute of obsessed people who chase their mission to its illogical conclusion.</p><h1>Lie #2 ‚Äì You‚Äôre missing some key bits of information</h1><p>I‚Äôve helped 6000+ people start writing online.</p><p>At the start I thought they were all missing some key strategy or insight that I could provide them. I‚Äôve since learned people are drowning information.</p><p>Low performers keep acquiring more information and never implementing it because they fear failure. I came across an example yesterday.</p><p>Guy tells me he wants to build an online empire. He mentions he‚Äôs about to start his third degree (Master's) at age 40. He says the latest degree has drained his bank account and his family is struggling financially.</p><p>I politely told him if he wanted to join my inner circle he might not fit in because most of my community don‚Äôt believe in college degrees anymore. In his case he‚Äôs onto his third degree and still getting zero results while dealing with the pain of poverty.</p><p>He blew up at me when I told him this.</p><blockquote><p>‚ÄúNever meet your heroes. You piece of sh*t, Denning.‚Äù</p></blockquote><p>An even bigger sign of a low performer is when they‚Äôre easily offended at a harmless remark like ‚Äúyou may not like our community.‚Äù</p><p>This example illustrates perfectly why more information isn‚Äôt the answer. Credentialism has led to people overloading their brains with more information, so they turn into adult babies who lack emotional intelligence and the ability to deal with failure or rejection.</p><pre><code>Obsession driven by daily habits backed by systems will get you 10x further than more information from a professor.</code></pre><p>It‚Äôs lonely being a high performer because most of the world thinks they lack information. Asking for permission and following the proven path is the default, which only leads to us becoming overwhelmed and drowning in busyness.</p><p>If you can stop being an information wh0re and digitally hoarding mountains of information, you will change the world.</p><h1>Lie #3 ‚Äì People are fearless</h1><p>When you compare yourself to people on social media, it‚Äôs easy to think everyone‚Äôs winning and you‚Äôre not. This is untrue.</p><p>People aren‚Äôt fearless.</p><p>In the surveys I‚Äôve run for the last 5 years around writing and online business the pattern has always been the same.</p><p>We‚Äôre afraid of:</p><ul><li><p>Failing</p></li><li><p>Imposter syndrome</p></li><li><p>Not feeling like an expert</p></li><li><p>Not being experienced enough</p></li><li><p>Being trolled or getting hateful comments</p></li></ul><p>The average person never gets over these fears. They prevent them from ever taking action and they never learn that it‚Äôs their fear holding them back. When you have the privilege of interacting with people from all walks of life you learn the truth.</p><pre><code>Most people are destroyed by their fears.</code></pre><p>There are very few fearless people in the world. I consider myself fearless. It makes me lonely at times. I can only name 2-3 other people who I consider to be fearless.</p><p>It makes me feel like an outlier.</p><p>As a result, I can‚Äôt comprehend how people can possibly stay in dead-end jobs when each day they‚Äôre slowly dying and their bodies are breaking down with age.</p><p>So I have to have fewer friends.</p><div><hr></div><p>Last weekend I went to a lunch with my wife‚Äôs friends. </p><p>I sat in the corner playing with my 1 year old because I couldn‚Äôt relate to the other people. They sat there and complained about their careers.</p><p>One of them even shared how his employer missed paying his salary the week prior. The whole company didn‚Äôt get paid. Their employer is struggling to pay their bills. Salaries finally got paid 4 days later because the company won a trademark infringement court case.</p><p><em>All I could hear were alarm bells.</em></p><p>The guy heard nothing. He went back to work. ‚ÄúShe‚Äôll be right.‚Äù I give his employer 4 weeks before they go into liquidation. He doesn‚Äôt want to change because he‚Äôs comfortable, so he just bullsh*ts himself to keep going to the office.</p><p>If you can learn to overcome fear you can easily join the top 1%.</p><h1>Lie #4 ‚Äì The market is saturated</h1><p>I lied. This one is true.</p><p>But the market is saturated with low quality, piss poor crap. Excellence used to be the way. Humans used to make beautiful stuff. Now we churn out billions of widgets that all look the same and can serve a function, sure, but inspire no one.</p><div class="captioned-image-container"><figure><a class="image-link image2 is-viewable-imag" target="_blank" href="https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F02a6b2a4-372c-4527-b78d-c15f66b14fe9_1549x2027.jpeg" data-component-name="Image2ToDOM"><div class="image2-inset"><picture><source type="image/webp" srcset="https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_424,c_limit,f_webp,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F02a6b2a4-372c-4527-b78d-c15f66b14fe9_1549x2027.jpeg 424w, https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_848,c_limit,f_webp,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F02a6b2a4-372c-4527-b78d-c15f66b14fe9_1549x2027.jpeg 848w, https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_1272,c_limit,f_webp,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F02a6b2a4-372c-4527-b78d-c15f66b14fe9_1549x2027.jpeg 1272w, https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_1456,c_limit,f_webp,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F02a6b2a4-372c-4527-b78d-c15f66b14fe9_1549x2027.jpeg 1456w" sizes="100vw"><img src="https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_1456,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F02a6b2a4-372c-4527-b78d-c15f66b14fe9_1549x2027.jpeg" width="1456" height="1905" data-attrs="{&quot;src&quot;:&quot;https://substack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com/public/images/02a6b2a4-372c-4527-b78d-c15f66b14fe9_1549x2027.jpeg&quot;,&quot;srcNoWatermark&quot;:null,&quot;fullscreen&quot;:null,&quot;imageSize&quot;:null,&quot;height&quot;:1905,&quot;width&quot;:1456,&quot;resizeWidth&quot;:null,&quot;bytes&quot;:627892,&quot;alt&quot;:null,&quot;title&quot;:null,&quot;type&quot;:&quot;image/jpeg&quot;,&quot;href&quot;:null,&quot;belowTheFold&quot;:true,&quot;topImage&quot;:false,&quot;internalRedirect&quot;:null,&quot;isProcessing&quot;:false}" class="sizing-normal" alt="" srcset="https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_424,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F02a6b2a4-372c-4527-b78d-c15f66b14fe9_1549x2027.jpeg 424w, https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_848,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F02a6b2a4-372c-4527-b78d-c15f66b14fe9_1549x2027.jpeg 848w, https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_1272,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F02a6b2a4-372c-4527-b78d-c15f66b14fe9_1549x2027.jpeg 1272w, https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_1456,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F02a6b2a4-372c-4527-b78d-c15f66b14fe9_1549x2027.jpeg 1456w" sizes="100vw" loading="lazy"></picture><div class="image-link-expand"><svg xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg" width="20" height="20" viewBox="0 0 24 24" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2" stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" class="lucide lucide-maximize2 "><polyline points="15 3 21 3 21 9"></polyline><polyline points="9 21 3 21 3 15"></polyline><line x1="21" x2="14" y1="3" y2="10"></line><line x1="3" x2="10" y1="21" y2="14"></line></svg></div></div></a><figcaption class="image-caption"><em>Image Credit-Culture Critic via X</em></figcaption></figure></div><p>It‚Äôs most obvious with architecture. Buildings used to be beautiful. Now they‚Äôre depressing brutalist concrete blocks that are soulless and make humans feel like machines. So the market is saturated but with depressing offerings.</p><p>I operate in the online business and writing niches. What scares me isn‚Äôt the market, it‚Äôs how bad most products and services are.</p><p>There‚Äôs little to no effort. They‚Äôre slapped together in a few hours, then wrapped in sensationalist irresistible marketing that‚Äôs nothing more than broken promises. It feels lonely sometimes to see how uninspiring the market really is.</p><p>The upside is this creates an opportunity for us to build something inspiring. It doesn‚Äôt even need to be great. A 1%-better-product or service is enough to win in a saturated market.</p><blockquote><p>Saturated Markets = Huge Opportunity</p></blockquote><p>Being inspiring with what you do in a world full of rock-bottom creativity feels lonely. Paradoxically, it‚Äôs led to the start of a new renaissance that you can join.</p><h1>Lie #5 ‚Äì I‚Äôll start in 2025</h1><p>I heard this for the first time the other day.</p><p>The mediocre-middle-of-the-road love to delay goals to someday, one day. They‚Äôre going to get started. Just not right now. They‚Äôre busy.&nbsp;&nbsp;Timing isn‚Äôt right. They‚Äôre getting their ducks in a row (they probably should shoot those ducks in the head).</p><p>If not now, then f*cking when?</p><p>What‚Äôs so special about 2025 compared to 2024? It‚Äôs lonely in high performer land because we don‚Äôt delay goals. If it‚Äôs a goal it‚Äôs a priority for today. If it‚Äôs not a goal then we stop thinking about it and ma$turbating over it. There‚Äôs no in between.</p><blockquote><p>Most people have too many goals. Too many bright ideas.</p></blockquote><p>It‚Äôs better to have one goal and forget all the other shiny objects. But this way of thinking is uncommon. When I tell people I‚Äôm 10 years into my writing goal and have 30+ years to go, they think I‚Äôm crazy. The mission is overly simplistic. There‚Äôs no chopping and changing. It‚Äôs driven by pure obsession.</p><p>A reader emailed me yesterday. ‚ÄúTim, I think you‚Äôve lost touch with what people are going through. You‚Äôve made too many millions of dollars.‚Äù</p><p>Maybe they‚Äôre right. That thought makes me even lonelier. I don‚Äôt understand distractions and shallow work done in a noisy office where you can‚Äôt think.</p><p>What the reader said next made more sense. They said they didn‚Äôt know how I could write online and lose all of my privacy. They didn‚Äôt get how I could play what they call the ‚Äúsocial media game.‚Äù</p><p>But I have plenty of privacy. Most people who do what I do use a nickname. My friend Dan Koe is a great example. You didn‚Äôt think his real name was Dan Koe, did you? Lol. It‚Äôs a made up name.</p><p>Social media isn‚Äôt some Squid Game to me either. I‚Äôm online building an empire around my obsession which feels effortless. So it‚Äôs not some useless game I play to make money. Money never was the goal.</p><p>When you have clarity on what you love doing, the desire to delay it until next year or some future point when you‚Äôre dead becomes a crazy idea.</p><p>You either start the goal today or never. If you choose today it‚Äôs the most lonely path.</p><h1>Closing Thought</h1><p>I don‚Äôt mind being lonely.</p><p>To me, there‚Äôs nothing worse than being stuck in a crowd of people who want to fit in while simultaneously wasting their lives away achieving nothing.</p><p>Then following the crowd to a sports game to get drunk and try to forget about their lack of progress, only to wake up with a hangover on Monday morning to relive Groundhog day once more on repeat until retirement followed by death ~10 years later.</p><p>Choose the lonely path. Dare to implement high-performance habits that‚Äôll make you weird.</p><p>Tell me which of the lies above resonated the most and why in the comments.</p><p>P.S. Want to get more followers on Substack? LinkedIn? X?&nbsp;</p><p>Want to write your daily posts in minutes (or seconds) instead of hours?</p><div><hr></div><p>You gotta come to my free masterclass next week.&nbsp;</p><p><a href="https://event.webinarjam.com/register/69/gp84gs6w">Click here to reserve your spot.</a></p><p>(Limited seating. Book your spot and be sure to show up on time)&nbsp;</p></body></html>	High performance often feels lonely due to lack of competition, information overload, and fear of failure. The market is saturated with low-quality offerings, creating an opportunity for inspiring work. Delaying goals until the future is a common mistake. Choosing the lonely path of high performance can lead to a new renaissance.	2024-10-10 19:18:46	2024-10-11 14:01:41.689	2024-10-11 14:01:43.033	{english}	https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2Fb03c8cad-ea12-4bd1-bf08-08dad0ebb560_1042x667.jpeg	Tim Denning	being-a-high-performer-is-lonely-as-hell
